title: Elastic Scattering of 104 MeV Alpha Particles

x4freetext: Elastic Scattering of 104 MeV Alpha Particles

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nuclear Physics, Section A, Vol.128, p.81 (1969)

x4freetext: The targets used were partly foils and partly gaseous.
In all cases the isotopic ndance of the target isotope
was about 99%. All foil targets were circular, 14 mm
in diameter. The thickness of the foil targets was
measured by weighing by measuring the energy loss of
24lAm alpha-particles. The gas targets were cylindrical
sealed off containers made of brass and sized
140 mm diam. x 35 mm. A 10 mm high slit that ran almost
all around the cylinder and that was covered by a
6 mu-m thick havar foil providing an entrance and exit
for the primary beam and the scattered particles. These
target containers were filled to approximately 1
atmosphere.  The effective target thickness was defined
by the 1.7x6 mm entrance slit of the detector and a
second 3 mm wide slit placed 225 mm in front of the
Si(Li) detectors of area 100 mm2. The detectors
were mounted inside a copper block of 38 mm diameter
with an entrance slit of 1.7 x  10**6 mm2 at a distance
of 300 mm from the target center.

x4freetext: The errors in the individual experimental
results include the statistical error which is
negligible for most points and an error due to the
uncertainty of the angle of measurements (0.1 degr.).
This error is due to the uncertainty of the angular
scale zero and was converted into an error of the
cross section by multiplying it by the slope of the
